description:
Given two nodes of a binary tree p and q, return _their lowest common ancestor (LCA)_.

Each node will have a reference to its parent node. The definition for Node is below:

class Node {
    public int val;
    public Node left;
    public Node right;
    public Node parent;
}

According to the [definition of LCA on Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lowest_common_ancestor): "The lowest common ancestor of two nodes p and q in a tree T is the lowest node that has both p and q as descendants (where we allow a node to be a descendant of itself). "

solutionCode.javascript:
    ```javascript
class Node {
    constructor(val=0, left=null, right=null, parent=null) {
        this.val = val;
        this.left = left;
        this.right = right;
        this.parent = parent;
    }
}

function lowestCommonAncestor(p, q) {
    let a = p;
    let b = q;
    while (a !== b) {
        a = a.parent ? a.parent : q;
        b = b.parent ? b.parent : p;
    }
    return a;
}
```

    We initialize two pointers, `a` and `b`, to be the input nodes `p` and `q`. Then, we run a while loop which terminates when `a` and `b` meet. In each iteration, we move `a` to its parent if it exists, otherwise we move it to node `q`. Similarly, we move `b` to its parent if it exists, otherwise we move it to node `p`.

Since we are traversing each node's ancestors and switching to the other node's ancestors, eventually `a` and `b` will meet at the lowest common ancestor of the two input nodes. This method ensures that we cover nodes up the tree and helps find the LCA in O(h) time, where h is the height of the tree.

solutionCode.java:
    ```java
class Node {
    public int val;
    public Node left;
    public Node right;
    public Node parent;
}

public Node lowestCommonAncestor(Node p, Node q) {
    Node a = p;
    Node b = q;
    while (a != b) {
        a = a.parent != null ? a.parent : q;
        b = b.parent != null ? b.parent : p;
    }
    return a;
}
```

    We initialize two pointers, `a` and `b`, to be the input nodes `p` and `q`. Then, we run a while loop which terminates when `a` and `b` meet. In each iteration, we move `a` to its parent if it exists, otherwise we move it to node `q`. Similarly, we move `b` to its parent if it exists, otherwise we move it to node `p`.

Since we are traversing each node's ancestors and switching to the other node's ancestors, eventually `a` and `b` will meet at the lowest common ancestor of the two input nodes. This method ensures that we cover nodes up the tree and helps find the LCA in O(h) time, where h is the height of the tree.
